    <item>
      <title>The AoN/Epic 1.0 issue in Plane of Fear, Absor does not know about it</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Necromancers&amp;message.id=9244#M9244</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;The Necromancer, Shaman and Shadow Knight Epic 1.0 quests require items from one of the four Plane of Fear Golems which also happen to drop the Bazaar money making item Amulet of Necropotence.&amp;nbsp; The Golems are killed on most servers as soon as they repop.&amp;nbsp; There is currently some friction between players seeking Epic 1.0 quest items and players seeking the Amulet of Necropotence.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;There are no good guys and bad guys in this scenario even though many would argue so.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Nonetheless, The fact that this scenario exists is enough reason for it to be evaluated by the Everquest developers.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;If a veteran developer like Absor does not know about it, perhaps more /feedback should be sent.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;It might be a good idea to inform the Everquest designers through feedback and forum posting that a debate does exist as a first step towards some progress.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&lt;A href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&amp;amp;message.id=296858#M296858" target=_blank&gt;http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&amp;amp;message.id=296858#M296858&lt;/A&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;BR&gt;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------&lt;BR&gt;KilljoyMcCoy wrote:&lt;BR&gt;Wow you fixed this whole thing in just 2 hours? Faction, quest givers, dialog, mobs, plus testing? Editing tables, making backups, verifiying, getting feedback from co-workers...I'm not being sarcastic, either.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;At that rate, you could crank out a fix for the SK/NEC/SHM epic roadblock / AoN permacamping problem in about 12 minutes. &lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Cut n' paste a similar encounter, change the mob names, zone names, turn in peices, reward...set the spawn spot, timer, and viola! Everyone is happy &lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Absor &lt;BR&gt;EQ Designer&lt;BR&gt;Posts: 547&lt;BR&gt;Registered: 03-01-2004 &lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;It helped that I knew the zone set up and wrote most of the docs for the zone.&amp;nbsp; So no poking around figuring stuff out, that saved me a lot of the usual time.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Testing it wasn't too hard, and the actual data change was pretty simple.&amp;nbsp; Our QA department will look over the changes, and odds are they'll find something I missed and I'll have to fix that.&amp;nbsp; &lt;STRONG&gt;For something like the epic roadblock you mentioned, I don't know what it is, where it is or anything much about it.&lt;/STRONG&gt;&amp;nbsp; So just the research for it would take a while.&amp;nbsp; It's way easier to work on something you know about than something you've never touched.&amp;nbsp; In fact, probably the hardest part is figuring out if a change is even needed.&amp;nbsp; Since I knew what should have been going on in Icefall, I could tell from the post I read that something was wrong.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Figuring out IF something should change, what that change should be and how to bring about the change is often the longest part of anything we have to fix.&amp;nbsp; There's nothing worse than implementing the wrong fix (or a fix to a problem that wasn't really a problem).&amp;nbsp; Changing stuff you're familiar with cuts the exploration factor way down.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;A - provider of information you never really wanted.&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
